      "content": "{\"claim\": \"The collapse was triggered by a pandemic-driven demographic collapse that unraveled the palace redistributive economies by decimating the specialized labor force, making administrative continuity impossible.\", \"mechanism\": \"A virulent, multi-wave plague (possibly ancestral to bubonic plague) swept through the dense palatial centers and their dependent settlements. The high mortality among scribes, artisans, and soldiers broke the chain of specialized knowledge and surplus extraction. Without enough laborers to work the fields or administrators to manage storage and redistribution, the economic system seized up. Famine followed not from drought but from a lack of manpower to harvest. Elite authority evaporated as rituals and offerings failed to stop the sickness, leading to the abandonment of depopulated centers without widespread destruction.\", \"scope\": {\"covers\": [\"Mycenaean palace centers (Pylos, Mycenae)\", \"Hittite capital Hattusa\", \"Ugarit\"], \"excludes\": [\"Egypt\", \"Cyprus (initially)\"]}, \"forbidden\": [{\"case\": \"Archaeological evidence shows a significant increase in grain storage capacity and diversification of food sources in the decades immediately preceding the destruction of Pylos and Hattusa.\", \"eval\": \"rubric:std-hist\"}, {\"case\": \"The destruction layers at all major sites are consistently and solely attributable to a single, massive earthquake storm with no evidence of prior social stress or burning.\", \"eval\": \"rubric:std-hist\"}], \"prose_notes\": \"This account explains the rapidity and selectivity of the collapse by the density-dependent spread of disease in centralized, urbanized palatial economies, while Egypt's more dispersed rural population along the Nile was less severely impacted. It reframes the 'Sea Peoples' as survivors fleeing plague-ravaged, empty cities.\"}"
